{
  "texts": [
    "First, the terms describing the static model and those for perturbations can vary by orders of magnitude.",
    "Thus, by excluding equilibrium terms we avoid important numerical precision problems.",
    "This method also avoids the numerical diffusion acting on equilibrium quantities.",
    "Secondly, the boundary conditions are easier to implement for the equations for perturbations (see Section 3.7).",
    "Finally, if the equilibrium is computed numerically, a full-variable simulation may still evolve despite the zero perturbation due to the numerical errors in the derivatives."
  ]
}